Chapter 7 - How an LLM Answers a Question
Objective

To understand the complete journey of a user's question inside an LLM-based application.

Step 1 – User Input

The user enters a question.

Example:

Explain Gradient Descent.

This is plain text.

Step 2 – Prompt Construction

The application does not send only the user's message.

It first builds a prompt.

Example:

System Prompt:
You are an experienced AI professor.

User Prompt:
Explain Gradient Descent.

Instruction:
Use simple language.
Give examples.
Explain mathematically.
Provide interview questions.

This complete prompt is sent to the LLM.

Step 3 – Tokenization

The LLM converts the prompt into tokens.

Example:

Explain
Gradient
Descent

Every token receives a numerical token ID.

Step 4 – Embedding

Each token ID is converted into an embedding.

An embedding is a dense numerical vector representing the token in a high-dimensional space.

The model operates on embeddings rather than raw text.

Step 5 – Transformer Processing

The embeddings pass through multiple Transformer layers.

Inside these layers, the model:

Understands context.
Learns relationships between words.
Predicts the next token.
Step 6 – Token Generation

The model predicts the next token.

Example:

Gradient

Then predicts:

Descent

Then predicts:

is

Then predicts:

an

This process repeats until the response is complete.

Step 7 – Detokenization

The generated tokens are converted back into readable text.

The user finally sees:

Gradient Descent is an optimization algorithm...

